This paper deals with security and privacy issues in mobile crowdsensing, which falls under the category of computer security and cryptography (cs.CR). The paper specifically focuses on location-related attacks, which suggests that it may also fall under the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI) as location information is often shared and utilized in social networks. The use of fingerprints and visiting patterns for location identification and detection of attacks suggests that it may also fall under the sub-category of networking and internet architecture (cs.NI) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), respectively. Finally, the use of emulated datasets and experiments on crowdsensed data suggests that it may also fall under the sub-category of multimedia (cs.MM) as multimedia data is often used in crowdsensing applications.
